Step3:Train two networks¶

3-1 CNN model training¶

In [10]:
def create_vanilla_cnn_model():
  inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
  x = data_augmentation(inputs)

  x = layers.Rescaling(1.0 / 255)(x)

  x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
  x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)

  x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
  x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)

  x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
  x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)

  x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
  x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)

  x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
  x = layers.Flatten()(x)

  x = layers.Dense(256, activation="relu")(x)

  x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
  outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)

  model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

  model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", optimizer="rmsprop", metrics=["accuracy"])

  return model

In [17]:
# new model using VGG16 as the base, freezing all layers except the top four layers
conv_base.trainable = True
for layer in conv_base.layers[:-4]:
    layer.trainable = False

inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = data_augmentation(inputs)
x = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(x)
x = conv_base(x)

x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dense(256, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)

model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", optimizer=keras.optimizers.RMSprop(learning_rate=1e-5),
                metrics=["accuracy"])
model.summary()

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay
import numpy as np

def evaluate_model(model, test_dataset):
    predictions = model.predict(test_dataset)
    predictions = np.round(predictions).astype(int)
    true_labels = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_dataset])

    print(classification_report(true_labels, predictions, target_names=["Cat", "Dog"]))

    cm = confusion_matrix(true_labels, predictions)
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=["Cat", "Dog"])
    disp.plot(cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
    plt.show()

print("Vanilla CNN Performance:")
evaluate_model(vanilla_cnn_model, test_dataset)

print("Fine-Tuned VGG16 Performance:")
evaluate_model(finetuned_vgg16_model, test_dataset)

Visualize the precision-recall tradeoff for both models.¶

In [22]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve, auc

def plot_precision_recall_curve(model, test_dataset):
    true_labels = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_dataset])
    predictions = model.predict(test_dataset).flatten()

    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(true_labels, predictions)
    pr_auc = auc(recall, precision)

    plt.plot(recall, precision, marker=".", label=f"PR AUC = {pr_auc:.2f}")
    plt.xlabel("Recall")
    plt.ylabel("Precision")
    plt.title("Precision-Recall Curve")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

print("Vanilla CNN Precision-Recall Curve:")
plot_precision_recall_curve(vanilla_cnn_model, test_dataset)

print("Fine-Tuned VGG16 Precision-Recall Curve:")
plot_precision_recall_curve(finetuned_vgg16_model, test_dataset)

Display specific examples where the model made incorrect predictions to understand weaknesses.¶

In [23]:
def display_failure_cases(model, test_dataset):
    predictions = model.predict(test_dataset)
    predictions = np.round(predictions).astype(int)
    true_labels = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_dataset])
    images = np.concatenate([x for x, y in test_dataset])

    incorrect_indices = np.where(predictions.flatten() != true_labels)[0]
    print(f"Number of incorrect predictions: {len(incorrect_indices)}")

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    for i, idx in enumerate(incorrect_indices[:9]):
        ax = plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(images[idx].astype("uint8"))
        plt.title(f"True: {true_labels[idx]}, Pred: {predictions[idx]}")
        plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()

print("Vanilla CNN Failure Cases:")
display_failure_cases(vanilla_cnn_model, test_dataset)

print("Fine-Tuned VGG16 Failure Cases:")
display_failure_cases(finetuned_vgg16_model, test_dataset)

  2. VGG16 belongs to pre-trained model, so it demonstrated better than Vanilla CNN.
